<h1>Ghana</h1>

<p>
	Despite previous announcements, which had came from career bureaucrats within Ghanaian government hinting on a possibility for crypto-currencies to be legalized, in January 2018 the Central Bank's official representative announced that trading and using digital money in Ghana stops to be legitimate and will be persecuted.
</p>
<p>
	For a country with a reputation for embracing technological creativity this ill-advise resolution promulgated by orthodox officeholders won't do more than just decelerating innovations. It will also be impossible to fully implement as Internet penetration rate continues to grow rapidly granting easy access to various detection avoidance tools. Meanwhile, Bitcoin is forced to go underground in Ghana.
</p>

<p>
	Business Notes for Startups Founders:
	<ul>		
		<li>political climate: marginally friendly;</li>
		<li>economic climate: moderately friendly;</li>
		<li>regions to focus: locally, Sub-Saharan Africa;</li>
		<li>industries to focus: e-commerce, media, mobile applications, e-job, marketplaces, entertainment, FinTech, tourism, solar, bio-tech;</li>
		<li>major limitations: relatively low Internet penetration (under 30%), high level of corruption, low personal income, limited access to VC and seed money;</li>
		<li>stimulus: expanding economy (GDP growth rate about 6%), many new market opportunities, large young population, access to qualify pool of local coders and talents from neighboring countries, potential to became one of major African's technological hubs.</li>
		<li>opportunities: many;</li>
		<li>Cryptocurrencies and ICOs (outlook): not legal (negative).</li>
	</ul>
</p>

